title: For Sale:  RARE MIDA Castelli 1889 TypeII
postcontent: Here is a WWl and WWll Revolver made by MIDA/Castelli of Brescia Italy in 1916. The 10.4 mm cartridge (sometimes called the 10.35 mm) was made for the French Chamelot-Delvigne design Italian Model 1874 revolver. The Model 1889 is a descendent of the Model 1874 and was designed by Carlo Bode who in 1886 had obtained a patent for a revolver and it was intended as an improved version of the 1874. There were about 70 variants over its life time from 1889 until 1945 however there are three basic types. This is the "A" type with folding trigger and no trigger guard. It has the octagonal 4.5" barrel. It is also the single/double action version. 6 shots. Mechanically this revolver is in excellent condition and the mechanism is tight and feels very good.

title: For Sale:  Ruger M77 MKII - .308 Win w/Bushnell Elite 4200
postcontent: This is a stainless Ruger M77 MKII with a laminated wood stock that I bought new in 2003.  Caliber is .308.  The wood stock is still nice, with just a handful of light handling marks.  The sporter weight barrel is 22" long.I had the gun worked over by Dave Bruno right after I bought it and before I ever shot it.  He free floated the barrel, glass bedded the action and did a trigger job on the gun.  The trigger is set at about 2.5 pounds, with no creep and it breaks clean and crisp.  I added a strap on cheek piece and a Pachmayr recoil pad.The gun is topped with a 1.5x6x36 Bushnell Elite 4200 scope with a duplex reticle and Rainguard coated lenses.  There is one mark on the scope as seen in the pictures.  This does not affect function.  The glass is clear and field of view is exceptional, especially at lower power settings.  This is an ideal setup for PA woods hunting where a high magnification scope hurts more than it helps.Large field of view = See the deer, kill the deer.This gun performs at it's best with 165 and 168 grain bullets.  I have load data.  No disappointments.  $675 OBO.  Thanks for looking.
